"Implement the following plan:\n\n# Plan: Detect and repair disconnected metadata branches during CLI commands\n\n## Context\n\nPR #511 prevents the empty-orphan bug going forward, but users who already hit the bug and continued working have a local `entire/checkpoints/v1` with real checkpoint data on a completely disconnected history from remote (no common ancestor). Currently PR #518 handles this in `EnsureMetadataBranch` during `entire enable`, but this is the wrong place — detection should happen during the CLI commands that actually need the metadata branch (explain, rewind, resume, etc.).\n\n**Diverged is fine** — local and remote share a common ancestor but each has unique commits. This is normal multi-dev flow, handled by the push path's tree merge. **Disconnected is the bug state** — no common ancestor, only caused by the empty-orphan bug. This needs detection and repair.\n\n## Approach\n\n### Detection\n\nCheck if local and remote `entire/checkpoints/v1` are disconnected using `git merge-base`:\n\n```\ngit merge-base <local-hash> <remote-hash>\n```\n- Exit 0 → shares ancestry (diverged or one is ancestor of other) → no action\n- Exit non-zero, no output → disconnected → repair needed\n\n### Repair: cherry-pick local commits onto remote tip\n\n1. Walk local branch from tip to root, collect commits (oldest-first)\n2. Skip the initial empty orphan commit (empty tree, no useful data)\n3. Reset local branch to remote tip\n4. For each local commit:\n   - Compute new entries: flatten commit's tree, subtract parent's tree entries\n   - Apply new entries onto current tip's tree\n   - Create new commit preserving original message/author\n5. Update local branch ref\n\nThis works because checkpoint shards are unique paths (`<id[:2]>/<id[2:]>/`) — cherry-picks always apply cleanly. Preserves linear commit history and individual commit messages.\n\n### Where detection runs\n\n**Once per process**, triggered at the strategy layer when the checkpoint store is first accessed. Uses `sync.Once` to avoid redundant `git merge-base` calls.\n\n**Call sites:**\n1. `ManualCommitStrategy.getCheckpointStore()` (`manual_commit.go:47`) — covers all strategy-mediated reads and writes (explain, rewind, resume, clean, condensation)\n2. `getBranchCheckpoints()` (`explain.go:888`) — bypasses strategy, creates own GitStore\n3. `ListCheckpoints()` (`strategy/common.go:112`) — opens own repo, reads branch directly\n\n### User-facing output\n\n```\n[entire] Detected disconnected session metadata (local and remote share no common ancestor)\n[entire] Cherry-picking 3 local checkpoint(s) onto remote...\n[entire] Done — all local and remote checkpoints preserved\n```\n\n## Files to modify\n\n### New file: `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`\n\nDetection + cherry-pick repair:\n\n- `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch(repo *git.Repository) error` — main function\n- `isDisconnected(repoPath, hashA, hashB string) bool` — uses `git merge-base` (not `--is-ancestor`)\n- `collectCommitChain(repo, ref) []*object.Commit` — walks parents to root, returns oldest-first\n- `cherryPickOnto(repo, base plumbing.Hash, commits []*object.Commit) (plumbing.Hash, error)` — applies each commit's new entries onto base\n\nReuses: `checkpoint.FlattenTree()`, `checkpoint.BuildTreeFromEntries()`, `GetGitAuthorFromRepo()`\n\n### New file: `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile_test.go`\n\nTests using existing `initBareWithMetadataBranch` and `cloneWithConfig` helpers:\n\n- `TestReconcileDisconnected_NoRemote` — no-op\n- `TestReconcileDisconnected_NoLocal` — no-op\n- `TestReconcileDisconnected_SameHash` — no-op\n- `TestReconcileDisconnected_SharedAncestry` — no-op (diverged, not disconnected)\n- `TestReconcileDisconnected_Disconnected` — creates disconnected orphan with local checkpoint, verifies after repair: linear history on top of remote, both local and remote data present\n- `TestReconcileDisconnected_MultipleLocalCheckpoints` — 3 local commits, all cherry-picked\n\n### Modify: `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`\n\n- Add package-level `sync.Once` gate: `ensureMetadataReconciled(repo)`\n- Export: `EnsureMetadataReconciled(repo *git.Repository) error` — for callers outside strategy package\n- Remove `syncMetadataBranch` call from `EnsureMetadataBranch` (move that logic to the new reconcile function)\n- Keep `isAncestorCLI` — still useful for the fast-forward case\n- Add reconciliation call to `ListCheckpoints()`\n\n### Modify: `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit.go`\n\nIn `getCheckpointStore()`, add after `OpenRepository`:\n```go\nif err := ensureMetadataReconciled(repo); err != nil {\n    fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \"[entire] Warning: %v\\n\", err)\n}\n```\n\n### Modify: `cmd/entire/cli/explain.go`\n\nIn `getBranchCheckpoints()`, add before `checkpoint.NewGitStore(repo)`:\n```go\nif err := strategy.EnsureMetadataReconciled(repo); err != nil {\n    // Log but don't fail — reads may still work\n}\n```\n\n## What happens in `EnsureMetadataBranch` after this change\n\n`EnsureMetadataBranch` (called during `enable`) keeps only:\n- Create local from remote when local doesn't exist (PR #511)\n- Replace empty orphan with remote (PR #516)\n- Create empty orphan when neither exists\n- Error handling for non-ref-not-found errors\n\nThe disconnected/diverged reconciliation logic (`syncMetadataBranch`) is removed — that responsibility moves to `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch`.\n\n## Verification\n\n```bash\nmise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test:ci\n```\n\nSpecific tests:\n```bash\ngo test ./cmd/entire/cli/strategy/ -run TestReconcileDisconnected -v\n```\n\nManual verification:\n1. Clone repo with remote checkpoints\n2. Create disconnected local branch (orphan with different data)\n3. Run `go run ./cmd/entire explain --no-pager --commit <hash>`\n4. Verify reconciliation message appears and explain succeeds\n\n\nIf you need specific details from before exiting plan mode (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /Users/dvydra/.claude/projects/-Users-dvydra-src-cli/229c0af5-5604-44a0-a6ae-795bdcb0d95b.jsonl\n\n---\n\ncreate the PR\n\n---\n\nwait - are there aother commits from before now on this branhc? do you still need them? e2aa1739c0e366d5826805223537082a270b28c3 and e2aa1739c0e366d5826805223537082a270b28c3\n\n---\n\nmake sure the active logic is all capture in the PR Text\n\n---\n\ncan you review this \n\nhttps://github.com/entireio/cli/pull/533#discussion_r2861704417\n\nIs that a new problem or something where you should be checking the error type\n\n---\n\ncool. now let's do this one\n\nisDisconnected returns true for any non-zero exit from git merge-base, but git merge-base uses exit code 1 for \"no common ancestor\" and exit code 128+ for actual errors (corrupt repo, invalid hash, context timeout). Since the function has a 10-second timeout, a slow git merge-base invocation or any other transient error will be misinterpreted as \"disconnected,\" which triggers the cherry-pick branch rewrite in ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch. Distinguishing exit code 1 from other non-zero codes would prevent spurious reconciliation.\n\n---\n\nthis is comment a problem for the Entire usecase?\n\nThis “new entries only” diff (paths present in commit but not in parent) drops modifications and deletions. Metadata commits can replace existing blobs and delete old chunk files (e.g., UpdateCommitted/Finalize transcript), so reconciliation would lose updates and/or leave stale files. Compute/apply a full diff vs parent (adds + modifies + deletes) instead of additions-only.\n\n---\n\ndoes this complicate the cherry-picking and mean it might fail in some conditions?\n\n---\n\nIf isEmptyMetadataBranch fails, EnsureMetadataBranch silently skips updating the empty orphan from remote. That can leave the repo in a broken state and hide corruption/missing objects. If checkErr != nil, return a wrapped error so callers can surface/handle it.\n\n---\n\nis this a problem?\n\nEnsureMetadataReconciled declares reconcileErr as a local variable on each invocation. On the first call, sync.Once executes the closure and sets it. On subsequent calls, reconcileOnce.Do is a no-op, so reconcileErr stays at its zero value (nil). This means if reconciliation fails, only the first caller sees the error — all later callers silently receive nil, and reconciliation is never retried.\n\n---\n\ndid we already fix this\n\nIf isEmptyMetadataBranch fails, EnsureMetadataBranch silently skips updating the empty orphan from remote. That can leave the repo in a broken state and hide corruption/missing objects. If checkErr != nil, return a wrapped error so callers can surface/handle it.\n\n---\n\nand this one? \n\nReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch treats any error reading the local metadata ref as “no local branch” and returns nil. This can silently ignore real repository/ref store errors. Only treat plumbing.ErrReferenceNotFound as the expected no-branch case; otherwise return a wrapped error.\n\n---\n\nOkay, do a holistic review of the whole PR. And paste the results here.\n\n---\n\n1. [metadata_reconcile_test.go:405-414] Fragile file-creation logic uses error as control flow\n\n  The test tries to write a file, catches the error to create the directory, then retries.\n  Should just be os.MkdirAll then os.WriteFile.\n\n---\n\n2. [common.go:48-59] sync.Once global state is not resettable for testing\n\n  No resetReconcileOnceForTest() function exists (unlike resetProtectedDirsForTest). If any\n  integration test triggers EnsureMetadataReconciled via getCheckpointStore() or\n  ListCheckpoints, a stale cached result will leak to subsequent tests.\n\n---\n\n3. [metadata_reconcile.go:83-91] Silent continue on tree error swallows real errors\n\n  When filtering empty-tree commits, c.Tree() errors are silently skipped. A corrupted tree would\n   cause a data commit to be silently dropped during repair. Should at least log a warning.\n\n---\n\n4. [metadata_reconcile.go:194] Best-effort FlattenTree on parent silently ignores errors\n\n  If FlattenTree fails partially, parentEntries is incomplete. The delta computation then treats\n  unread entries as \"deleted\" and produces an incorrect cherry-pick. Since this is a data repair\n  operation, the error should propagate.\n\n---\n\n5. [metadata_reconcile.go:144-167] collectCommitChain silently stops at MaxCommitTraversalDepth\n\n  If local metadata branch has >1000 commits, chain is silently truncated — older data is lost\n  without warning. Should return an error when the limit is hit without reaching a root commit.\n\n---\n\nwhen would the commit chain exceed a depth limit in this code path?\n\n---\n\nis this overkill then?\n\n---\n\n6. [common.go:55-59] EnsureMetadataReconciled captures first repo forever\n\n  The repo parameter is only used on the first call. Subsequent calls with different repos\n  silently ignore the parameter. Consider removing the parameter and having it open its own repo\n  internally (like ListCheckpoints does).\n\n---\n\nReconciliation messages use fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr) directly while project guidelines prefer\n   the logging package for operational messages.\n\n---\n\nisDisconnected creates its own context.Background() instead of accepting a caller context.\n\n---\n\nEnsureMetadataBranch silently returns nil when it detects a non-empty diverged state — no\n  logging that disconnected state was noticed. this should be to the logs not the output\n\n---\n\nThis session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.\n\nAnalysis:\nLet me trace through the entire conversation chronologically:\n\n1. User asked to implement a plan for detecting and repairing disconnected metadata branches during CLI commands. The plan was detailed and specified new files, modifications, and the approach.\n\n2. I created task items and started implementing:\n   - Create